Vim (short for **Vi IMproved**): keyboard-driven text editor used in Linux and Unix-like systems. Unlike standard editors, it is **modal**, meaning keys perform different actions depending on which "mode" it operating on.
- Normal Mode (Default):** For navigation and executing commands (e.g., copying, deleting). Press `Esc` to return here from any other mode.
- **Insert Mode:** For typing text normally. Press `i` in Normal Mode to enter.
- **Command-Line Mode:** For saving, quitting, and advanced settings. Press `:` in Normal Mode to enter.
- **Visual Mode:** For selecting blocks of text to manipulate (cut/copy). Press `v` for characters, `V` for lines, or `Ctrl+v` for blocks
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Basic Commands Reference

| Action          | Command        | Explanation                                                |
| --------------- | -------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| Open File        `vim filename`       Opens an existing file or creates a new one.               
| Save              :w                  W**rites (saves) changes to the disk.                    
| **Quit            :q                  Q**uits the editor (fails if there are unsaved changes). 
| **Save & Quit     :wq` or :x`         Saves and exits in one step.                               
| Force Quit        :q!                 Quits without saving any changes.                          
| Undo               u                  U**ndoes the last action.                                
| **Redo           Ctrl + r             R**edoes the action you just undid.  
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
**Navigation & Editing
In Normal Mode, you use specific keys to move around without mouse around.
- Basic Movement:** `h` (left), `j` (down), `k` (up), `l` (right).
- **Word Jumps:** `w` (start of next word), `b` (start of previous word), `e` (end of current word).
- **Line Ends:** `0` (beginning of line), `$` (end of line).
- **File Ends:** `gg` (top of file), `G` (bottom of file).
- **Deleting:** `x` (character), `dw` (word), `dd` (entire line).
- **Copy/Paste:** `yy` (yank/copy line), `p` (paste after cursor), `P` (paste before cursor). 
 **Search and Replace
- Search:** Type `/` followed by your word (e.g., `/error`) and press `Enter`. Use `n` for next match and `N` for previous.
- **Global Replace:** `:%s/old/new/g` replaces every occurrence of "old" with "new" in the entire file.
**top and htop :- are command-line utilites used for real-time system monitors in Linux, displaying CPU usage, memory consumption, and list of running processes.
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
The `top` Command
`top` (Table of Processes) is the traditional, built-in tool found on almost every Unix-like system. 
- Availability:** Pre-installed by default; no manual installation is usually required.
- **Interface:** Basic, monochrome text-based display.
- **Key Shortcuts (Interactive):
    - P: Sort by **P**rocessor (CPU) usage.
    - M: Sort by **M**emory usage.
    - k: **K**ill a process (requires entering the PID).
    - q: **Q**uit the application.
    - z: Toggle color/monochrome mode. 
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
The `htop` Command

`htop` is a modern, interactive process viewer that serves as an enhanced alternative to `top`. 

- Installation:** Usually requires manual installation (e.g., `sudo apt install htop`).
- **Interface:** Features a color-coded UI with visual bar graphs for CPU cores, RAM, and Swap.
- **Interactive Features:** Supports mouse clicking and scrolling (vertical and horizontal) to see full command lines.
- **Function Key Shortcuts:
    - F3: **Search** for a specific process.
    - F4: **Filter** processes by name.
    - F5: Toggle **Tree view** to show parent/child relationships.
    - F6: Open the **Sort** menu to select columns easily.
    - F9: **Kill** a selected process directly via a signal menu. 
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Key Differences
|Feature|top|htop|
|---|---|---|
|Default Install|Yes (standard on most distros)|No (usually needs installation)|
|Visuals|Plain text / monochrome|Colored bars and graphs|
|Mouse Support|No|Yes|
|Scrolling|Limited (keyboard only)|Full horizontal/vertical scrolling|
|Process Tree|Basic (hidden by default)|Rich, interactive tree mode (F5)|
Nano** is a simple, beginner-friendly command-line text editor for Linux and other Unix-like systems. Unlike more complex editor like Vim, nano is **modeless, meaning you can start typing immediately after opening it without switching between "insert" and "command" modes.
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Interface & Navigation
- Shortcuts: Common commands are listed at the bottom of the screen.
- Key Symbols:The caret symbol (^) represents the **Ctrl** key, and **M** represents the **Meta** key (usually **Alt** or **Esc).
- Movement: Use the arrow keys for basic navigation or **Page Up/Down** to scroll.
_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Essential Shortcuts
|Task|Shortcut|Description|
|---|---|---|
|**Save|Ctrl + O|"Writes Out" the current buffer to the file.
|Exit|Ctrl + X|Closes nano; prompts to save if changes were made.
|Help|Ctrl + G|Opens the full built-in help manual.
|Search|Ctrl + W|"Where is" search tool to find text in the file.
|Replace|Alt + R|Finds a term and allows you to replace it.
|Cut Line|Ctrl + K|"Kuts" (deletes) the current line.
|Paste Line|Ctrl + U|"Uncuts" (pastes) the last cut line.
|Undo/Redo|Alt + U / E|Undo or redo your last action.
_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Advanced Tips

- Open at Specific Line: Use `nano +line_number filename` to jump straight to a specific line.
- Read-Only Mode: Open a file with `nano -v filename` to prevent accidental edits.
- Disable Line Wrapping: When editing system configuration files, use `nano -w filename` to prevent automatic word wrapping, which can break configs.
