IP address (Internet Protocol address) 
it is a unique numerical label assigned to every device on a network. It serves two main purposes: identifying the device and providing its location so that data packets can be sent to the correct destination.

IP Address Classes
Traditionally, IPv4 addresses (32-bit numbers usually written as four decimal segments like 192.168.1.1) were divided into five classes (A through E) to accommodate networks of different sizes. The class is determined by the value of the first octet. Usable host can be calculated using $2^n - 2$

| Class [3, 8, 9, 10, 11] | First Octet Range | Default Subnet Mask | Use Case                                        |
| ----------------------- | ----------------- | ------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Class A                 | 1 – 126           | 255.0.0.0           | Very large networks (e.g., global corporations) |
| Class B                 | 128 – 191         | 255.255.0.0         | Medium to large networks (e.g., universities)   |
| Class C                 | 192 – 223         | 255.255.255.0       | Small networks (e.g., home or small office)     |
| Class D                 | 224 – 239         | N/A                 | Reserved for Multicast (sending data to groups) |
| Class E                 | 240 – 255         | N/A                 | Reserved for Experimental and research use      |

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
## Public vs. Private IP Addresses

Addresses are also categorized by where they are used:

- Public IP: Assigned by your ISP and visible to the entire internet.
- Private IP: Used only within your local network (LAN) and not routable on the public internet. Common ranges include:
    
    - Class A: 10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255
    - Class B: 172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255
    - Class C: 192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255
 Shift to IPv6
Because the world ran out of unique 32-bit IPv4 addresses, IPv6 was introduced. It uses a 128-bit format (e.g., 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334) and provides a virtually infinite number of unique addresses, eliminating the need for complex address classes in modern networking.
